{
  "Idea": "We propose the Recall-Oriented Functional Coverage Score (RFC-Score), a novel evaluation framework for code generation models that prioritizes recall by measuring the extent to which generated code candidates cover the space of functionally correct behaviors. Unlike traditional metrics such as pass@k, which reward precision (i.e., presence of at least one fully correct solution), RFC-Score emphasizes functional completeness—ensuring that all possible correct logic paths are represented across the output set, even if no single candidate passes all test cases. The score is computed in three stages: (1) Behavioral Clustering, where generated programs are executed against a rich set of test inputs (including edge cases and symbolic constraints) to extract runtime behaviors (e.g., control flow traces, variable states); (2) Functional Equivalence Grouping, where clustering algorithms group outputs into equivalence classes based on semantic similarity using graph kernels over program dependence graphs or embeddings from code2seq models; and (3) Coverage Aggregation, where the RFC-Score is calculated as the proportion of known correct behavior clusters (derived from ground-truth solutions and human-validated variants) that are represented in the model's output distribution. Crucially, partial matches—such as correct logic missing only error handling or off-by-one fixes—are mapped to their corresponding clusters and credited, thus incentivizing broad exploration. This approach enables fine-grained diagnostic insights: e.g., identifying whether a model consistently misses recursive base cases or fails to handle null inputs. RFC-Score can be used to compare models not just on 'how often they get it right,' but 'how completely they understand the problem.' When integrated into training loops, it could guide reinforcement learning or filtering mechanisms to favor diverse, semantically rich outputs. Potential impact includes improved benchmarking standards, better alignment with developer needs in IDE plugins, and enhanced data collection for iterative model refinement. We validate RFC-Score on HumanEval, MBPP, and APPS+, showing strong correlation with expert judgment on functional coverage while revealing limitations in current high-pass@k models that overlook behavioral diversity.",
